12.title: Pre-election periods
12.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Pre-election periods

About the term “purdah” 

The term ‘purdah’ is often used unofficially to describe the period immediately before an election or referendum when there are restrictions on the activity of civil servants. 

Although you may still hear the word ‘purdah’ used across the Civil Service, due to the connotations of the word, we prefer to use the term ‘pre-election period’.

During pre-election periods there are some things that government departments and civil servants should avoid doing or be careful doing.
Although The Civil Service Code of Conduct permanently binds Civil Servants, the code’s core values should be observed even more closely during pre-election periods. These are:
integrity - putting the obligations of public service above your interests
honesty - being truthful and open
objectivity - basing your advice and decisions on rigorous analysis of the evidence
impartiality - acting solely according to the merits of the case and serving equally well governments of different political persuasions.
Researching in pre-election periods
Typically, most user research activities can continue in pre-election periods as user research supports service delivery against a defined policy. However, there are some subjects and methods that researchers should avoid.
User researchers working on more exploratory types of research should be particularly cautious in their research approach. For example, you may be working on a policy or service that has not been formally announced to the public or could be considered more contentious in the run-up to an election.
During a pre-election period, you can:
recruit members of the public through recruitment agencies, as long as initial adverts and screeners do not mention or imply that the research is for a government service
invite participants from existing user research panels - this is especially helpful for any sensitive research 
use internal channels to recruit colleagues for user research on internal aspects of services.

During a pre-election period you cannot
research themes or issues that might be raised by politicians or be of interest to lobby groups, or could impact the outcome of elections. This may change depending on the type of election (general election or local elections); for example in local elections researching a topic where local authorities do service delivery, e.g. children’s social care or LA-maintained schools
recruit participants directly online, for example, through government or personal social media accounts
do any pop-up research where you recruit users on the day
promote user research activities outside the department, or publish results on blogs or other public channels.


Although the Civil Service code should always be applied when carrying out research on behalf of the department, during a pre-election period, you should especially:
keep contact with users limited to operational communications only (e.g. for recruitment purposes or to provide updates on research session details)
continue to be mindful of how you use social media - ‘likes’ on social media can be seen as direct endorsements, and any posts or comments made are also open to public scrutiny.
be careful about what you discuss with users during research sessions - steer away from any political discussion or commentary. If users express a political opinion, remain neutral and professional and explain you are unable to comment if you are invited to
Further guidance
As long as your research is not contentious and cannot possibly influence the outcome of an election, it’s generally safe to proceed during a pre-election period. However, it’s advisable to err on the side of caution and to sense-check your research with your team.
If you are unsure whether your research is ‘safe’, raise a project risk with your service’s Delivery Manager, or speak to a Lead User Researcher for advice on how you can manage or mitigate risk. Specific workarounds may work for your service, meaning research can go ahead, e.g. by using proxy participants and testing non-politically sensitive parts of the service.
In some instances, it may be necessary to get an agreement to proceed with the Senior Responsible Officer (SRO) or other Deputy Director who has accountability for your service. The Lead User Researchers can advise whether this is necessary, and your Delivery Manager can arrange this.
In addition to this guidance, the Cabinet Office publishes guidance on the conduct of civil servants in the pre-election period relating specifically to the type of pre-election period.
GDS also has guidance on conducting research with specific user groups and how to handle confidential subjects during pre-election periods.

13.title: Doing user research under the Civil Service code
13.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Doing user research under the Civil Service code
The Civil Service code is a set of core values and principles all civil servants must work to when carrying out their official duties, regardless of role or grade.
The Civil Service is integral to the government of the United Kingdom and supports the government in developing and implementing policies, and delivering public services.
As a civil servant, you are expected to carry out your role with dedication and a commitment to the Civil Service and its core values set out in the Code. These are:
integrity - putting the obligations of public service above your interests
honesty - being truthful and open
objectivity - basing your advice and decisions on rigorous analysis of the evidence
impartiality - acting solely according to the merits of the case and serving equally well governments of different political persuasions.
Working in line with these values allows civil servants to support good government and to gain and retain the respect of ministers, Parliament, the public and its customers (users).
Although the Code should be observed at all times, there are special considerations for conducting user research during a pre-election period.
If you feel you are being asked to work in a way which conflicts with the values set out in the Code, you have a right to challenge or raise a concern.
Doing user research for the Department for Education
As well as observing the Civil Service code, the department expects all staff to have high standards of behaviour and conduct. All employees have a responsibility to manage themselves and their staff in line with the department’s policies and procedures.
As user researchers in the department, we work to a set of agreed principles which help to guide us in our work. By applying these principles, we can ensure we’re working in line with the Civil Service code, the department’s expectations of us as employees, while also delivering a consistent approach to user research in the department, helping to deliver the department’s strategy and vision to:
put children and learners first
empower yourself and others
be data, evidence and expertise driven 
deliver joined up results
Using social media in research
Social media is a helpful tool to use in combination with other tools and methods available to us as user researchers, but there are restrictions on how we can use social media in our work.

14.title: What user researchers do
14.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



What user researchers do
User research is a qualitative research specialism which can help teams to learn about their users, and to create services and policies that meet their needs.
User research is a specialist skill set, and is not just ‘talking to someone’. User researchers have a range of skills which allow them to plan, design and carry out research activities with users that help teams get a deep understanding of the people that use government services. This research informs policy, proposition, service, content and interaction design so that services work well for users and achieves policy intent.
If you are already a user researcher or you are interested in the profession, find out how to connect with the user research community.
What user research can help you to do
User research can help you to:
understand the problems you are trying to solve
decide if/what services to build
help you to ensure the service that you create will work well for users, and also meet the policy intent and business goals
The better you understand your users, the more likely you are to design and build a service that works well for them, and that meets business goals.
Visit the GDS Service Manual to find out more information on user research in government.
http://ddat.businesspartners@education.gov.uk

15.title: Our principles

16.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];

Research Operations
Research Operations (ReOps) are a central team who supports the work of user researchers in the department. The team is responsible for producing the tools, capability and guidance to allow researchers to do their best work.

Research Operations is the mechanisms and strategies that set user research in motion. It provides the roles, tools, and processes needed to support researchers in delivering and scaling the impact of the craft across an organisation" - Emma Boulton

The Research Operations team in DfE work closely with the user research community to co-create solutions to some of the common challenges and barriers researchers face. Research Operations and the research community also collaborate to put things into motion, enabling researchers to enact the values they hold.
Our vision statement:

We will enable user researchers to do their best work more efficiently, improving their happiness and wellbeing and increasing the overall quality of the services we deliver.

We will do this by:


making it easier to find previous research and insight to waste less time, avoid duplication, improve the quality of research outputs, and help user researchers and teams make better decisions. 
helping user researchers access the participants they need, making recruitment quicker and more cost-efficient, and enabling research with a more diverse set of users.
directing user researchers to process, guidance, and templates, to support them in delivering high-quality research safely, legally and ethically 
ensuring all user researchers have access to specialist research spaces and the right equipment so that they can perform the best research 
leading in Research Operations practise and thinking across the UK government and the world.

Read more about our vision and missions [LINK TO MISSION DOCUMENT].
We plan our delivery strategy around the priorities of user researchers. You can see what we’re working on currently and what we have planned for the future in our backlog [LINK TO BACKLOG] and our roadmap [LINK TO ROADMAP].
The team
Tom Adams, Head of User Research


Leads on user research and Research Operations strategy in the department.

Alice Kiernan, Research Operations Lead


Leads on the Research Evidence Directory, the user research knowledge base, knowledge and insight management, user research onboarding, professional principles, managing internal and external ReOps stakeholder relationships and oversees the work of the ReOps team.

Emma Christoforou, Research Operations specialist


Leads on the department’s approach to participant recruitment for user research, with a focus on inclusive and diverse recruitment. 



Got a suggestion or feedback for us? Get in touch

More about Research Operations
Research Operations is not unique to DfE and is a global profession established by Team ReOps.
Read about the eight pillars of user research that underpin the ReOps framework and ReOps map.
Other government departments also have Research Operations teams and have an active cross-government Slack community [LINK TO X-GOV SLACK].
Find out more about Research Operations in Government.

17.title: Communities of practice
17.content:

Communities of practice
User Research communities of practice are spaces (both in-person and virtual) for researchers to come together to share best practices and mix with people from across the profession.
They give researchers a chance to:
learn from each other
share work and knowledge
meet new starters
support each other
hear from a range of voices from across the community
access learning and development opportunities
have visibility of the user research leadership team 
get essential updates about user research at DfE
How meetups work
Community of practice meetings (known as “meetups”) are time-boxed sessions which follow a similar structure each time. They run at both a national and a local level. The content of meetings differs depending on which you attend, and each local community has its way of doing things.

        
          
National
Local

Share knowledge and skills within the community and with other professions
Share experience and support with researchers in that area

Discuss challenges and best practices relevant to the whole community
Discuss things related explicitly to researchers in each locale

        
      Becoming an active member is a good way of shaping how your local community does things.
National meetings have a community of practice working group, which plans sessions and works with hosts and presenters to help them get the most out of the sessions. Hosting and presenting are available on a one-off/semi-regular basis and open to researchers of all grades and backgrounds. Senior User Researchers should host at least one session per year.
If you’re interested in hosting or presenting at a national meeting or being a part of the working group, contact Chardai Brice to learn more about how the team can support you to deliver a great session or steer the future of national meetups.
Getting involved
Meetups are held in person and remotely.
To get a calendar invite for any community of practice, ask one of the organisers listed.

        
          
Area
Frequency
Organisers

National
First Thursday of the month, 1-2 pm
Chardai Brice

Manchester and Sheffield
First Thursday of the month, 1-2 pm
Jude Eccles, Rachael Sumner

London
First Thursday of the month, 1-2 pm
Tom Crooks-Smith, Keisha Herbert

        
      There are currently no local communities in Bristol, Coventry, Darlington, Newcastle and Nottingham. If you are a researcher in any of those locations, please contact Keisha Herbert to discuss which local community would be best for you to join.
Some sessions are recorded to give everyone in the community a chance to access the content.  Watch recordings of previous meetups.
Another way of keeping involved with the user research community is through the community channels on the Department for Education’s Slack:
 #user_research
 #mcr-userresearchers
 #sheffield_user_researchers
 #ldn_userresearch
There are also  cross-government communities that publish blog content and hold meetups.

18.title: Using social media for user research
18.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Using social media for user research
Social media has proven an invaluable tool in user research, helping us to gather insight into users and their environments, proving to be a powerful source for desk research.
As user researchers, we can learn a lot from how people interact and engage through social media. We can see the experiences of users “in the moment” and (to an extent) in context, without needing to bring users into a research setting. In this sense, the data social media can provide is - in many ways - unfiltered, unaffected by research power dynamics, and accessible, with users sharing their experiences and emotions authentically, in their own words and in their own context.
Social media is a helpful tool to use in combination with other tools and methods available to us as user researchers.
Uses of social media in user research
As a user researcher, you can use social media to:
gather insight on groups and users you are interested in researching with, as secondary data - especially during a discovery or requirements-gathering phase of research
track search terms and analytics data relating to your research subject, identify the language and sentiment expressed by users 
share quotes and insights with your wider team to help contextualise users’ experiences of your service/product
monitor how a situation or scenario changes over time (for example, trending topics)
understand potential pain points and experiences of users, based on the information they choose to share publicly
get quick and free insight into your users

You cannot use social media to:
approach individuals or groups directly to recruit users for your research
draw conclusions on all users’ experiences of services or products
rely on the accuracy of self-reporting by users


Although we can learn a lot from accessing publicly available information and sentiments on social media, as user researchers in the Department for Education, we do not recruit via social media. This is in order to protect the wellbeing of researchers and to protect the department’s reputation.
Recruiting via social media platforms can leave individual researchers open to negative backlash and ethical challenge and members of the public can feel uncomfortable if researchers recruit through social media groups or by directly approaching them. Directly approaching one group or individual over another on social media could be seen as favouritism or a lack of impartiality, especially in research where incentives are being used.
Similarly, by using social media as a recruitment channel, we may be more prone to recruiting those who have a larger presence, following or influence online which can lead to bias and a lack of consideration around diverse and inclusive recruitment (for example, potentially excluding those users who predominantly or exclusively use offline parts of a service).
Although social media is not a tool we use for recruitment in the department, there are other approved methods of participant recruitment which can help you to find the users you need to research with.
As well as considerations around social media in user research, as civil servants we are expected to observe the Cabinet Office’s social media guidance at all times - both inside and outside of work, as well as following the department’s social media guidance and acceptable use of IT policy.
If your team is using social media as part of their communications strategy, the GDS social media playbook outlines ways of getting the most out of social media in our work as civil servants.

Power devices
The Power Device programme is designed to ensure that Civil Servants in specialist roles within DfE (including user researchers) are able to access more powerful devices which allow them to better do their work.
The programme allows users to request a more powerful and higher-spec Windows machine, or a Macbook to replace their existing standard device.
Requests must be underpinned by genuine business need and/or must be to replace inadequate existing kit (for example, Surface Pros which are 4 years or older and pose a security risk, or with insufficient spec to run required software for research).
Requesting a power device
Requests can be made via the Service Portal Power Devices form.
Requests for power devices should only be submitted following a discussion with one of the Lead User Researchers in your portfolio, or if you don’t have a Lead, you should discuss your requirements with the Head of User Research.
Please note that requests will be prioritised based on need and project urgency if there are limited devices available.


  !
  
    
Requests for power devices cannot be solely based on preference
  

Existing Macbooks
Some user researchers in the department already have access to Macbooks which were previously purchased by individual business areas.
If you currently have two devices (your Macbook and your Surface Windows device), you can ask to have your existing Macbook rebuilt so it can access all DfE services, allowing your Windows device to be returned to the department.
Requests for a rebuild of an existing Macbook can be made by filling in a non-standard request form via the Service Portal.

21.title: Digital tools
21.content:

Digital tools
There are a range of tools you will need when conducting user research. 
The Technology Directorate provides and supports DfE’s approved software and hardware.
Staff with access to our intranet can use the  Service Portal to request access to devices like laptops and smartphones, as well as productivity tools, like Office 365 and Skype for Business. Other software is also available to download through the Software Centre, found on your DfE device.
User researchers can also  request a power device if there is a business need for an upgrade to a more powerful device than the standard DfE Windows devices. 
If you are a contractor who needs a DfE device, you will need to ask a permanent member of staff (Grade 7 or above) within your team to request one for you.
If you have your own device which meets the requirements set out by IT’s policy, you can enrol onto the ‘Bring Your Own Device’ (BYOD) service. A permanent (Civil Servant) member of your team will need to complete a new starter request via the DfE Service Portal, noting that you wish to enrol onto BYOD.
Approved tools
The Transformation and Digital Directorate provides central licensing and support for certain additional tools where there is a business need. The Digital Tools Support team helps delivery teams with their tooling needs.
The Digital Tools Support team are in the process of assuring what tools are provided as part of the central toolkit for digital delivery teams. This may mean that new tools become available and existing tools are removed from use. Visit the team’s Wiki for the most up to date list of approved tools in the department.
Accessibility software and hardware supported by DfE is also available for users with an IT Workplace Adjustment, as well as a range of assistive software. Digital and Technology will also fund training for all new users of assistive software.

Tools that cannot be used
Miro (did not meet DfE security assurance)
Mural (did not meet DfE security assurance)
Zoom (did not meet Cabinet Office security assurance)


Accessing and requesting tools
In order to request an approved digital tool via the Digital Tools Support team you will need:

approval from your finance team
contact details of your Finance Business Partner
the name of your budget holder Deputy Director
your cost code
the name(s) of people needing access to the tool
to complete the relevant form
﻿The team will help you access an existing licence or set up a new licence for these tools.﻿
You can also contact them if a tool you need to use is not available, or if you already have access to digital tools and have questions.
Review the usage policy for digital tools, or email your DDaT Business Partner to discuss your requirements. Note that needs, rather than preferences, will be prioritised. Decisions about access to tools will be made on a case-by-case basis.﻿
There may be a cost involved with using these tools in your team, which your business area will need to justify and pay for.

59.title: Participant recruitment

60.title: Withdrawal of consent
60.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Withdrawal of consent
Research participants can withdraw their consent at any time. They can also make a Subject Access Request (SAR), this is where they ask to look at personal information that DfE holds about them.
Under UK GDPR, individuals have the right to know what personal information is held about them and have it deleted in some circumstances.
Withdrawing participants from research
A participant could withdraw consent at any time so you’ll need to make sure they know how.
You’ll also need to make sure you remind them that taking part in research is voluntary:
during recruitment
at the beginning and end of sessions
whenever you think they feel uncomfortable
Deleting research data
You’ll need to delete any research data related to a participant who has withdrawn their consent.
Delete your research data for the individual if:
they withdraw consent during a session (stop the session if this happens)
they withdraw consent after the session 
you notice at any point that you do not have recorded consent for them
When you delete someone’s data, make sure you:
put any completed paper consent forms in a confidential waste bin
delete related recordings, files and database entries
delete their personal information, including contact details, from any files
tell them you’ve deleted their data
You’ll be able to deal with requests much quicker if you keep your personal data files organised.
Dealing with Subject Access Requests (SARs)
An individual usually has the right to know what information is held about them by DfE. SARs are usually made to find out what information is being held and why.
If you’re dealing with a SAR you must respond to the requester within one month. You can choose to use a SARs response letter template to do this.
All SARs come through the ‘contact us’ service through Iris, DfE’s correspondence system. If you receive a SAR in a different way, email the Ministerial and Public Communications Division and ask them to log it.
Talk to the DPO or the UK GDPR policy team if you would like more specific advice about SARs.
Find out how to set up secure storage for files containing personal data.

61.title: Anonymising participant data
61.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Anonymising participant data
Anonymising personal data makes it easier for user researchers to use and share any data they’ve collected. Anonymising is removing the pieces of information that could be used to identify an individual.
If you anonymise your data then you can share it widely and store it without having to delete it later. Before you share, you’ll still need to check that participants have consented to having their anonymised data shared.
Anonymise notes as you make them
Most of the personal data can be anonymised whilst you’re collecting it. For file names and titles relating to the participant, you should use a unique identifier instead of their name.
Participants will often mention identifiable information during research, for example, the names of companies, colleagues, or the name of their child’s school. You can describe what they’ve said but you must remove any identifiable information.
Write your descriptions in square brackets to indicate that you’re not quoting verbatim. Some examples are:
?Royal Mail would become ‘[a large postal carrier’]
Someone’s name would become ‘[a colleague’]
Broad Oak primary school would become ‘[their child’s primary school’]
Remove details from audio and video
If you’re sharing video footage with your team or a wider audience, you need to anonymise it.
Edit the videos and remove any spoken personally identifiable information.  This includes the names, places, places of work, addresses. Make sure you know what personal data is.
You do not need to blur video or distort people’s voices but you must make sure a participant has consented to having their anonymised video shared. If they have not consented, delete the recording once you’ve taken notes/transcribed.
You can use MS Stream to edit video files. Recordings can be edited by either bleeping out this info, or just cutting out the part where this information is said.
You need to keep unedited recordings in the restricted personal data folder until you’ve fully anonymised them.
You only need to anonymise what you plan to share. Most recorded video sessions are not shared with others. It’s easier and quicker to only anonymise what you want to share, rather than anonymising everything you record. Recordings that you will not share can be deleted.
You must also check who the participant has agreed for recordings to be shared with. For example, they may have consented to sharing with the research team but not the wider DfE.
Once recordings have been fully anonymised, you can store them without a retention period in a less restricted folder like your team’s general folder.
Pseudonymisation is different to anonymising


Pseudonymisation is a technique that replaces or removes information in a data set that identifies an individual. It means personal data can no longer be linked to an individual without additional information.

Read the ICO definition of pseudonymisation.
An example of Pseudonymisation
It is best practice to anonymise data as soon as possible.
If you’re doing active research or you plan to contact a participant in the future, make sure you do not anonymise their data. In these cases pseudonymisation is a great security measure. But once you no longer need to contact the participants, you should anonymise or delete the data as soon as possible.
An example of using a unique identifier instead of a name could be using ‘P5R30502’ instead of the participant’s name, Joe Bloggs. Whilst you’ll know that ‘P5R30502’ took part in research, you would not know that P5R30502 is actually Joe Bloggs.
You’ll need to delete recruitment information to make sure the unique identifier cannot be linked to the participant name. For example, if you keep a recruitment tracker that says that Joe Bloggs took part in round 3 research on 5 February then you would be able to link the participant to the unique identifier.
In fact, even if you only know Joe Bloggs took part in round 3, there’s still a chance he’s identifiable. Pseudonymisation is effectively only a security measure. It does not change the status of the data as personal data.
Read more about pseudonymised data on the ICO website.
Delete consent forms after you’ve anonymised data
Due to the importance of consent forms it may seem scary to delete them.
If all your data is fully anonymised but you’re still storing consent forms, you’re still processing personal data.
Once you’ve fully anonymised (not pseudonymised) your participant personal data from your research, you should delete your consent forms.  DfE is developing training on how to delete consent forms, you should check with your user research lead that data is fully anonymised before deleting consent forms.
You may be concerned that a participant might want to withdraw their data or make a Subject Access Request (SAR) after you’ve anonymised it. There is no longer any data to delete or to send them as there is no way for you to identify it. This is normal practice and compliant with data protection. This is explained to the participant in our information sheet template which they read before research.
Consent forms should be the last piece of personal data you delete. If you cannot anonymise because you’re still contacting them, they must be deleted before the retention period ends regardless of whether you still need them.
Speak to your team before you share findings
Depending on what a participant has consented to, you can share anonymised findings with whomever you wish.
Leadership within DfE have decided that user researchers should always inform participants on how their data is being handled (and who it’s being shared with), including anonymised data.
Remember to always check that your team is happy to share the findings.
Contact Research Operations if you’re unsure what your consent form says.
It’s everybody’s responsibility to make sure the way they handle participant data is compliant with data protection laws.
Talk to your team and your user research lead if you have any concerns. <a href=“mailto:DP.ENQUIRIES@education.gov.uk”?Contact the Data Protection Office (DPO) if you have any concerns about UK GDPR.
Check how long you can keep personal information for.

62.title: Getting informed consent
62.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Getting informed consent
You need to get informed consent from participants if you want to process their personal data. Informed consent means making sure participants have had the right information about your research before they consent to taking part.
To comply with UK GDPR, you must get informed consent from participants if you plan to process their personal data.
How to get informed consent from your participants
To get informed consent you’ll need to send the participant an information sheet and a consent form in an accessible format at least a few days before the research session date. If they do not return it before the session, you’ll still be able to complete it with them before you start.
You can use the information sheet template from the template library
Getting informed consent means giving participants enough time to read the information sheet and think of any questions they might have.
You must tell them:
what they’ll be doing in the research
what data you’ll collect
what you’ll use it for
Confirm consent before each session
Before you start your session, remind the participant about the information they’ve read on the information seat and consent form.
You do not need to read them out verbatim. You might say:
are you still happy that we’ll share your anonymised data with the research team, relevant teams in DfE and HMRC?
we will store your information for up to 2 years but may delete it before then
are you still comfortable if we record this session and with any observers present?
Make sure you tell the participant:
what they’re consenting to
that taking part is optional
that they can withdraw at any time
how you’ll use the research data
Get consent for sharing their anonymised data
It is ethical best practice to inform participants about where their anonymised data is being shared, even though UK GDPR does not apply to anonymised data.
Participants may be comfortable sharing data with DfE but they may not wish to share it with HMRC.
They may also be comfortable with the research team seeing their faces and hearing their voice but might not want anyone at DfE to, even if they’re anonymous.
To make sure we comply with ethical best practice we give participants the option to consent to sharing anonymised data.
Get participant signatures
There are several different ways you can get participants to ‘sign’ their consent forms, you do not need to get a written signature to comply with UK GDPR.
The Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) says you can get participants to tick a checkbox to signify consent and still meet the rules.
Face to face sessions
Face to face sessions are a good opportunity to talk to participants about the research and make sure they know what they’re consenting to, but you need to make sure you’ve sent them the invitation letter and information sheet before the session. If they confirm they’re comfortable taking part then they can complete the paper consent form in person. You’ll need to make an electronic copy, keep it securely and dispose of the paper form in a confidential waste bin.
Sessions done remotely
For sessions done remotely, you can send the participant their consent form by email, survey link or by post.
For any postal consent forms you receive back, make an electronic copy, store it securely and dispose of any paper in a confidential waste bin.
You can get verbal consent as long as the participant has read the consent form and information sheet.  You’ll need to read out each statement from the consent form and get the participant to reply with their consent to each of the statements.  You’ll need to record this on video or audio and store the clips alongside any related consent documents from the participant.
Storing consent forms
Keep consent forms in the user research folder for personal data.
If you use Microsoft Forms for your consent forms, the data submitted will be stored on the Microsoft website. You should download a copy of the responses once the research sessions have finished and save them in the user researcher folder for personal data. Delete the data held on Microsoft Forms.
This means all the personal data is kept in one place and makes sure we’re able to delete data if user researchers leave the team or DfE without doing so
Consent forms: 
must be placed under the same retention period as all material that comes from the research session itself
should be the last document you delete when anonymising data or when the retention period is up
Find out more about managing personal data.
Find out what to do if a participant withdraws their consent.
Getting consent from children and vulnerable adults
For research with children and vulnerable adults you’ll need to get consent from the participant and from their parent, guardian, carer or responsible adult.
Talk to your Lead User Researcher if you have any concerns about this.

63.title: GDPR
63.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



GDPR
Personal data is information that could identify a living individual. It is different from anonymised data, which cannot usually be used to identify an individual.
User researchers at DfE regularly handle personal data. Organisations like DfE have a legal responsibility to protect personal data when they collect, process, store and erase it.
As a user researcher you need to make sure that you understand how to protect personal data to comply with UK General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
Types of personal data
User researchers are often responsible for collecting personal data about users but everyone at DfE has a legal responsibility to protect the data collected.
Some types of personal data that user researchers often collect are:
special category data (includes information about disability, race and sexuality)
addresses, occupations, dates of birth
unedited video or audio (raw data)
recruitment trackers which include names and contact details
IP addresses and any data from cookies
Identifying personal data
You need to make sure that you understand what personal data is so you can protect an individual’s information and follow the law.
Personal data is any information that could be used to identify a living individual. This includes information that could be used to indirectly identify someone when matched with other information about them.
In user research, personal data is referred to as: 
personal identifiers (PID)
personally identifiable information (PII)
raw data
User researchers should recognise that someone’s personal data also includes special category data, this is any information about race, ethnicity, sexual orientation or political views. Special category data needs a higher level of protection than ordinary personal data.
Principles to follow in user research
UK GDPR sets out responsibilities for organisations for collecting, processing, storing and erasing personal data. The aim of this law is to improve existing legal  protection over individual’s rights to their information in a data-driven, modern world.


UK GDPR follows 7 principles:
lawful, fairness and transparency 
purpose limitation (this means being clear about why you’re processing data) 
data minimisation (this means collecting the right amount) 
accuracy
storage limitation (this means not keeping data for any longer than you need it) 
integrity and confidentiality (security) 
accountability 


For user researchers, to follow the law and protect personal data you must:
make your reasons for collecting data clear to participants (this is informed consent)
only collect data when there is a lawful reason 
not reuse data that you’ve collected in the past 
only collect data that you will need and use
make sure data is accurate and delete any inaccurate data 
only keep data for the length of time that you need it for and tell participants what this is
keep it secure and only share it with people who need to know it
Who is accountable for the data (data controller)
If you’re processing personal or special category data in your role as an employee at DfE then DfE is accountable for the data and is the data controller.
What happens when you anonymise data
UK GDPR does not apply to fully anonymised data because after the process of anonymisation it can no longer be used to identify someone. It’s better to anonymise data as soon as you can.

64.title: Storing personal data
64.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Storing personal data
User researchers store digital files in SharePoint and Google shared drives.
Your team might already have this set up. If not, you’ll need to choose a place to keep participants’ personal data and request access to set it up. You’ll also need to make sure you carefully manage who accesses the files.
Choose a platform to store personal data
As a user researcher at DfE, you’ll use Google Drive and SharePoint to store files depending on how your team is set up. The platform you choose should be decided by your team. They might already be using a certain platform, so check with them before requesting anything new.
The Data Protection Office and security team at DfE recommend using SharePoint to store personal data. You should keep in mind that if you have contractors on your team they may struggle to access SharePoint.
You can choose one platform for files that have personal data in them and another for files without personal data, for example, project files.
SharePoint folder for user researchers
A new process is being developed where you’ll be able to choose to keep participant personal data in the SharePoint workplace for user researchers. With SharePoint, all personal data is kept in one secure place – this mitigates risk by making it easier to manage.
Research Operations have worked closely with the Knowledge and Information Management Team (KIM) to make it easier for you to manage personal data in SharePoint, including moving, setting permissions and deleting.
Using SharePoint helps keeps participant personal data safe because: 
you can only access this with an invitation link 
you’ll only be able to see the folders you’ve given access to 
nobody else will be able to access the data you store in SharePoint without permission 
you can use retention labels to make sure your data is automatically deleted at the end of a retention period - for example, if you set a retention label of ‘2 years’ the file will be automatically deleted after 2 years
Read about retention periods for keeping personal data.
Google shared drives
You may choose to keep personal data in Google Drive.
Unlike with Sharepoint, there’s no centrally managed folder (by DfE) for user researchers in Google Drive. You’ll need to create your own folders.
If you use Google Drive, Research Operations will not be able to see your folders or help you with managing access, so there is an increased risk to managing personal data. Do not add Research Operations colleagues to your folders because the way they are set up on the platform means there are too many for them to monitor.
The folder that you set up for personal data should be a Google shared drive.
Request access to shared drives
Fill out the new requests form or contact the digital tools team for more information. Anyone who needs access to the shared drive will need to have a digital.education.gov.uk account and it may take up to 48 to get access.
Do not contact individuals from the team directly, always use the #digital-tools-support Slack channel or email digital-tools-support@digital.education.gov.uk. This helps them manage their workload and get to your requests faster.
Manage who accesses the files
Only give others access to personal data that has not been anonymised on a ‘need to know’ basis.
Where possible, user researchers should be the only people accessing personal data. As a user researcher you should limit access to the data to the smallest number of people possible.
Give access to DfE information asset owners
DfE needs to keep up to date records of all the data it stores. Places where data is stored are called ‘information assets’. If they contain personal data, some examples of information assets are:
individual documents
folders containing multiple documents
a recruitment panel
an online service
All information assets should be recorded on the DfE information asset register.
Information asset owners (IAOs) are accountable for the security of data at DfE and they need to have access to folders containing personal data. IAOs are sometimes supported by information asset managers (IAMs). Some teams will have an IAM who is responsible for all of the personal data collected in user research.
Giving access to other people
Where it is not manageable for one researcher to conduct research and also manage all of the data compliantly, access can be given to someone who is not a user researcher, an IAO or an IAM, to help with data management. This person must understand UK GDPR and how it relates to good data management.
Anyone other than your team, an IAO or IAM can only be given access to personal data to help with compliance, never just to have access to research.
Find out how to anonymise personal data.

66.title: Protecting personal data
66.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Protecting personal data
Protecting personal data if your participant works in DfE
You still need to follow UK GDPR and protect the personal data of your participants if they work in DfE. This kind of user research is sometimes called ‘internal research’.
Types of internal research range from surveys about experiences like COVID-19 to research done to support an internal service or product like the DfE service manual.
Store their personal data
Personal data for internal research must be kept in the same secure and restricted folders where you keep external participant data.
Find out how to set up secure storage for files containing personal data.
Get consent to collect and use their data
You need to get consent from internal research participants to collect and use their personal data. You can use the consent form for external research to do this. A new form is being developed by the Research Operations team for getting consent for internal research.
Explain the purpose of your research to the participants, tell them what they’ll be asked about and what you’ll be doing with the data you collect.
You can ask them for feedback about their experiences working with your team. Make sure you explain this beforehand so they’re not pressured to give it when asked.
Anonymise the data
There are stricter rules for anonymising the personal data of internal participants than for external ones. It’s stricter because there is a risk that colleagues will be able to identify participants.
Make sure you only collect the data you need. When recording video and audio, voices may be recognisable to people who know the participant. Even if you blur out someone’s face, they may be identifiable from their clothing or accessories, for example, from something they wear every day like a wedding ring.

67.title: Retention periods
67.content:
window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
  function gtag(){dataLayer.push(arguments);}
  gtag('js', new Date());

  gtag('config', 'G-');



Retention periods
All personal data that you collect has a retention period, this is the amount of time you can keep it until you must delete it. If you anonymise personal data then it does not have a retention period.
You’ll need to check which retention period is appropriate for the data you’re collecting before you start your research. Only keep it for as long as you need it for or by the retention period end date.
Retention periods
You can set your own retention period when you submit your research plan.
2 year retention period (recommended for all)
The DfE user research profession recommends that you choose a retention period of up to 2 years for all the personal data you collect on any project. Keeping personal data for 2 years or less means you’ll have enough time to analyse the data. It also mitigates against risks caused by unpredictable pauses in projects due changes in circumstances or funding, for example the impact of COVID-19.
3 year retention periods
You may choose a retention period of up to 3 years in exceptional circumstances on larger projects. Only choose 3 years if it’s likely that you’ll need to use the data you’ve collected after 2 years but before 3 years whilst on the same project. You must have a good reason for why you’re not able to anonymise the personal data you’ve collected.
5 year retention periods
You may choose a retention period of up to 5 years in some exceptional circumstances. Only choose 5 years if your project is classed as ‘longitudinal’, this means you’ll need to use this personal data over a 5 year period on the project. Longitudinal projects usually involve sharing with other government departments or doing statistical analysis where data cannot be anonymised in the usual 2 to 3 year period.
Manage retention periods on your files
You must make sure that data is deleted once the retention period ends. The best way to remember to do this is by using labels on your electronic files to remind you when the retention period is due to end.
SharePoint folders
You’ll soon be able to choose to manage the retention period on your files using labels in SharePoint, this option is currently being developed. User researchers often use labels to manage their files, if you use the retention period labels then the data will be automatically deleted when the retention period ends.
Google shared drives
You cannot use labels in the same way if you keep your files in a Google drive. If you’re keeping personal data in a Google shared drive then you should set reminders in your calendar to remind you to remove the data by the end of the retention period.
If you’re leaving DfE, make sure you tell your team about any reminders you’ve set.
The retention period end date is a legal deadline for deleting data. You should aim to delete any anonymised data before the end of the retention period. Find out  how to anonymise data.

Accessibility legal requirements
To find out about the legal requirements you need to meet, check the guidance on the GDS Service Manual for making your service accessible.
Make sure your service is accessible
Almost a fifth of working age adults in the UK have a disability, and approximately a quarter of people in the UK will experience a mental health problem each year. You need to make sure everyone’s needs are considered when building a service.
All DfE’s services must:


be accessible to disabled people
have an accessibility statement that says which parts of its digital content aren’t accessible and why
have a way for people to tell the department if they find something that isn’t accessible
have details of the official enforcement procedure if users want to make a complaint 

The Cabinet Office and the Equalities and Human Rights Commission monitor DfE services and investigate any breaches to the rules. There will be legal implications if the department is found to be breaking the law.


For more support in this area, email the business engagement and accessibility team.

75.title: DfE accessibility support for services
75.content:

DfE accessibility support for services
DfE Accessibility team
The DfE accessibility team only support some of DfE’s services and systems directly but they’ll be able to help you with general advice on how to make your service more accessible.
If you’re looking for support or want to find out if the team can help you, email the business engagement and accessibility team at accessibility.support@education.gov.uk.
The team can give you advice about:


how to make your service more accessible
current legislation and how you can meet it to make sure your service is compliant
checking your service accessibility statement before publication
what you need to do if your service needs an accessibility assurance audit

Accessibility Community
You can sign up to Slack and join the DfE workspace to communicate and share ideas. Look at #accessibility channel, where the accessibility team share ideas, knowledge and issues around access to DfE services.
Share knowledge and experiences
The team want to get to a point where we’re sharing knowledge and experiences across government, setting up partnerships to improve accessibility together. To get to that point, we’ve got a lot to learn.
The team want to hear your feedback around accessibility. If you want to share ideas about how we can improve access to DfE services and better support you, email the business engagement and accessibility team at accessibility.support@education.gov.uk.
